{
  "texts": [
    "In Sect. 3.4, we show lensed SNe as a probe of dust in the foreground lens galaxy.",
    "Whilst it is accepted that a Type Ia SN is a thermonuclear detonation of a white dwarf (WD), the cause of the detonations remains uncertain even after decades of study (Maoz et al. 2014; Livio and Mazzali 2018).",
    "The classic progenitor model (often referred to as the single degenerate channel) for a Type Ia SN is a close binary of a white dwarf and a post main sequence star (Whelan and Iben 1973).",
    "As the star expands, it overflows its Roche lobe and its outer layers are accreted onto the WD until the WD reaches the Chandrasekhar mass.",
    "At this point, electron degeneracy pressure can no longer support the WD, and gravitational collapse causes thermonuclear detonation of the WD."
  ]
}